title.narrative: 202 TREATMENT OF ACUTE MALNUTRITION

description.narrative: By 2022, in UNICEF supported states, government and partners have enhanced capacity to scale up services for the treatment of severe acute malnutrition, which contributes to Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition, Early Detection And Treatment Of Malnutrition (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Data, Research, Evaluation And Knowledge Management, Evaluations, Research And Data, Partnerships And Engagement: Public And Private, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Business and Key Business Stakeholders demonstrate growing willingness, commitment and resource allocation for protecting and promoting child rights in policy and practice by 2022

description.narrative: UNICEF-led advocacy for delivering package of services for children with Sever Acute Malnutrition (SAM) resulted in decisions by State Governments to launch and intensify large-scale responses for early identification and management of children with SAM at community level in eight states (Assam, Chhattisgarh, Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh, Maharashtra, Rajasthan, Telangana, Uttar Pradesh). Four states (Bihar, Jharkhand, Odisha, West Bengal) have community-based programs for addressing SAM operational in select geographies. Guidelines for facility-based SAM management were updated. Plans for nation-wide orientation of Medical Officers through digital mode is under preparation. Total 447,000 children with SAM received community of facility based care services. | Status:Constrained | As-of Date:07/01/2022
